Q: How to list files in a directory using Bash?
A: ls -lh {{path/to/dir}}

For example:
$ ls -lh {{/path/to/directory}}

This will list the contents of the directory in human readable format, with the first column showing the path, the second column showing the size in bytes, the third column showing the last modified date and the fourth column showing the file permissions.

To get more information about a file, you can use the -l option:
$ ls -l {{path/to/file}}

This will display more detailed information about the file, including the content, permissions, and ownership.

